summary: After watching the Captain Marvel trailer, I’m thinking Captain Marvel might have something to do with Nick Fury losing his eye.
body:
After watching the Captain Marvel trailer, I’m thinking Captain Marvel might have something to do with Nick Fury losing his eye.

Because in CA:TWS, Nick told Steve that the last time he trusted someone, he lost an eye.

In the Captain Marvel trailer, we see a younger Nick Fury with both of his eyes.

And considering the dialogue in the trailer, it’s evident that Nick Fury needs Captain Marvel’s help.

So I’m thinking: what if Captain Marvel has something to do with Nick Fury’s lost eye? What if she is the reason he lost his eye?

title: "Captain Marvel" Vol.1-2 & "The Enemy Within"
body:
Hot on the heels of today’s Captain Marvel trailer release, we look back on the first time Carol Danvers took the name in our evergreen review.

With the hype machine for the new Captain Marvelmovie starting to ramp up, I thought it’d be a good time to go back and read the series that will act as the inspiration for the movie. In all fairness, it’s a bit difficult to follow the sequence of these volumes, as Marvel kept rebooting the series. That being said, I’m covering “Captain Marvel” volume 1 & 2, as well as “The Enemy Within”…

tags: not making this a marvel/dc post AT ALL but... they had all these comic book canon female superheroes at their disposal for years
summary: I love that Marvel finally made their first female superhero-centered movie, but you know that they weren’t brave enough to do...
body:
I love that Marvel finally made their first female superhero-centered movie, but you know that they weren’t brave enough to do so until they saw the reception of Wonder Woman

Like, in the 10 years of its mainstream movie existence, they couldn’t create a single female led superhero movie?? Most of the female superheroes ended up in Marvel TV, so they are less seen and appreciated by the greater public and tv is usually seen as a much lesser risk financially for studios
